If a point $\mathrm{P}(\alpha, \beta, \gamma)$ satisfying
<br/><br/>$$\left( {\matrix{
   \alpha  & \beta  & \gamma   \cr 

 } } \right)\left( {\matrix{
   2 & {10} & 8  \cr 
   9 & 3 & 8  \cr 
   8 & 4 & 8  \cr 

 } } \right) = \left( {\matrix{
   0 & 0 & 0  \cr 

 } } \right)$$
<br/><br/>lies on the plane $2 x+4 y+3 z=5$, then $6 \alpha+9 \beta+7 \gamma$ is equal to :

solution:
Let $Q(x, y, z)$ be the image of $P(1,2,3)$ in the plane
<br><br>$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp; 2 x-y+z=9 \\\\
&amp; \therefore \frac{x-1}{2}=\frac{y-2}{-1}=\frac{z-3}{1} 
 =\frac{-2(2 \times 1+(-1)(2)+(1)(3)(-9)}{(2)^2+(-1)^2+(1)^2}
\end{aligned}
$$
<br><br>$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp; \Rightarrow \frac{x-1}{2}=\frac{y-2}{-1}=\frac{z-3}{1}=\frac{-2(-6)}{6}=2 \\\\
&amp; \Rightarrow x=5, y=0, z=5
\end{aligned}
$$
